{Partner's 3\C bid is Stayman; with 4 cards in both Majors you respond 3\H. Partner now bids 3NT.   

Partner's 3\C bid is Stayman; with 4 cards in both Majors you respond 3\H. Partner now bids 3NT.   

Partner would not use Stayman unless he held a 4-card Major suit himself. Since he didn't like your \Hs it follows that he must have 4 \Ss.

So you correct the 3NT contract to 4\S. 

North plays 4\S. East leads the \DQ.

If you had left it in 3NT you'd have 8 top tricks and a \S finesse for 9.

But you're in 4\S.  

Loser List: \S = 1 : \H = 0 : \D = 1 : \C = 2 :: Total = 4

If you can guess the \SQ your problems are over. But just in case you dislike those 50% guesses, try to find a better Plan. 

Another possibility is that a defender holds either a singleton or doubleton \SQ so you can pick up the suit by leading \S A K. This is smaller than a 50% chance. 

But there is more to the odds than that. Suppose you try the second possibility and play off both the \SA and \SK but the \SQ does <b>NOT</b> drop. You are still not dead! You just leave the \SQ out there and start on \Hs. As long as the defender who holds the \SQ has at least 3 \Hs he will be unable to ruff until after you have discarded dummy's \D loser.

The extra chance makes this Plan your best hope.

You could have made the contract easily by playing West for the \SQ.

You could have gone down easily by playing East for the \SQ.

Or you could have made it whoever held the \SQ by using the "improved" plan.}
[Play "W"]DQ

